Introduction¶

Background¶

Before dating apps became all the rage, there was this thing called speed dating that was meant to be a fun way to cut down on the mountains of time individuals spent trying to find a partner. Speed dating was a solution that allowed one to meet and interact with a large number of potential partners in a relatively short amount of time -- often just 4 minutes, as in this experiment. In this report, I want to dissect what people are looking for in their speed dating matches, if there exist gender differences (which will be limited to male and female in this dataset), and other factors (such as the order in which people met potential partners) that might influence peoples' decisions.

Data¶

The dataset we will explore was drawn from "Speed Dating Experiment", found on Kaggle.com. Through a series of speed dating experiments conducted from 2002-2004 by Columbia Business School professors Ray Fisman and Sheena Iyengar for their paper Gender Differences in Mate Selection: Evidence From a Speed Dating Experiment, a dataset compiling demographics, dating habits, lifestyle information, and various attributes was collected. When participants signed up, they filled out a baseline survey. Then participants rated each other after each 4-minute interaction. Finally, individuals were asked if they would like a second date with any of the potential partners they met during the experiment, and rated them again on similar questions as their own baseline survey. Note that these experiments collected information from heterosexual male-identifying and heterosexual female-identifying individuals.

For more analysis from Iyengar and Fisman, read Racial Preferences in Dating.

  • 552 participants in the experiment from 2002-2004
  • Dates were 4 minutes long
  • Survey questions included in dataset:
    • If they would like to see their date again
    • Attractiveness
    • Sincerity
    • Intelligence
    • Fun
    • Ambition
    • Shared Interests
  • Participant information collected:
    • Demoraphics
    • Dating habits
    • Self-perceptions across key attributes
    • Beliefs on what others find valuable in a mate
    • Lifestyle information

Questions were asked in 3 stages:

  1. Before the date
  2. After the date
  3. 3-4 weeks after the date

Further reading:

  • https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20191112-how-dating-app-algorithms-predict-romantic-desire
  • https://www.vox.com/2019/2/7/18210998/tinder-algorithm-swiping-tips-dating-app-science?__c=1

gender_rslt.pvalue
Out[23]:
1.1102230246251565e-16

We can see in the plots above that men have a relatively similar rejection/match ratio, but women have a slightly higher rejection/match ratio, meaning that women tend to reject more men than they match with. Women received about 1750 "no" and about 1600 "yes" for the decision question "Would you like to see him or her again?". Men received 2050 "no" and 1300 "yes", meaning men are more likely to be rejected by women than women are to be rejected by men. These results are statistically significant, confirmed by the chi-square test. Next, we'll examine self-reported characteristic ratings, breaking our exploration down into 3 questions:

  1. What people say they look for most in the opposite sex
  2. What they think MOST of their fellow men/women look for in the opposite sex
  3. What they think the opposite sex looks for in a date

We will break this further down into 3 phases for both men and women:

  1. Before the date
  2. After the date
  3. 3-4 weeks after the date
In [202]:
# prepping data
def dataprep(dataset, cols):
    dataset2 = dataset[dataset[cols].notnull().all(1)]
    dataset2 = dataset2.groupby("gender").agg(AvgAttractive1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[0], aggfunc = np.mean),
                                          AvgSincere1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[1], aggfunc = np.mean),
                                          AvgIntel1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[2], aggfunc = np.mean),
                                          AvgFun1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[3], aggfunc = np.mean),
                                          AvgAmb1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[4], aggfunc = np.mean),
                                          AvgShar1 = pd.NamedAgg(column = cols[5], aggfunc = np.mean))
    # filtering for men
    perceptionsummary = perceptionanalysis(dataset2)
    perceptionsummary_male = perceptionsummary[perceptionsummary.index == 1]
    perceptionsummary_male['Score'] = pd.DataFrame(np.round(perceptionsummary_male['Score']))

    
    # filtering for women
    perceptionsummary_female = perceptionsummary[perceptionsummary.index == 0]
    perceptionsummary_female['Score'] = pd.DataFrame(np.round(perceptionsummary_female['Score']))
    
    return pd.DataFrame(perceptionsummary_male), pd.DataFrame(perceptionsummary_female)
In [25]:
# creates dataset of only rated characteristics
def perceptionanalysis(dataset):
    attractiveonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgAttractive1"])
    attractiveonly = attractiveonly.rename(columns = {"AvgAttractive1": "Score"})
    attractiveonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Attractive", "Attractive"]
    
    sincereonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgSincere1"])
    sincereonly = sincereonly.rename(columns = {"AvgSincere1": "Score"})
    sincereonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Sincere", "Sincere"]

    funonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgFun1"])
    funonly = funonly.rename(columns = {"AvgFun1": "Score"})
    funonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Fun", "Fun"]
    
    ambonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgAmb1"])
    ambonly = ambonly.rename(columns = {"AvgAmb1": "Score"})
    ambonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Ambitious", "Ambitious"]
    
    sharonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgShar1"])
    sharonly = sharonly.rename(columns = {"AvgShar1": "Score"})
    sharonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Shared Interests", "Shared Interests"]
    
    intelonly = pd.DataFrame(dataset.loc[:, "AvgIntel1"])
    intelonly = intelonly.rename(columns = {"AvgIntel1": "Score"})
    intelonly["Type of Attribute"] = ["Intelligent", "Intelligent"]
    
    return pd.concat([attractiveonly, sincereonly, funonly, ambonly, sharonly, intelonly])
In [231]:
def graphproducer(dataframe, cols, title):
    df = dataprep(dataframe, cols)[0]
    df2 = dataprep(dataframe, cols)[1]
    fig, (ax, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, sharey = False, constrained_layout = True)

    df.sort_values(by = "Score").plot(kind = "barh", x = "Type of Attribute", y = "Score", legend = False, ax = ax, title = "Men")
    df2.sort_values(by = "Score").plot(kind = "barh", x = "Type of Attribute", y = "Score", legend = False, ax = ax2, color = "gold", title = "Women", figsize = [10, 4])
    ax.set_xlabel("Score")
    ax2.set_xlabel("Score")
    fig.suptitle(title, ha = "center")

How Many Interactions Were Unrequited Love?¶

Meaning one party indicated they were interested but the other party declined. That is, wwhere dec_o = 1 and dec = 0 OR dec = 1 and dec_o = 0.

In [39]:
# unrequited love count
no_love_count = len(date4[(date4['dec_o']==0) & (date4['dec']==1)]) 
+ len(date4[(date4['dec_o']==1) & (date4['dec']==0)])
perc_broken_heart = no_love_count / len(date4.index)
perc_broken_heart*100
Out[39]:
26.040900397234072

This means that 26% of participants did not match with someone who indicated interest in them. This is higher than the percentage of people who got a second date.

Do the incidences of unrequited love differ according to attractiveness of the partner?

This heatmap confirms our assertion that attractiveness does not determine your likelihood of experiencing unrequited love. It looks like your attractiveness (attr3_1) is only weakly correlated with how attractive your date finds you (attr_o). In fact, there is nearly zero correlation between how smart your sincere you think you are versus how smart and sincere your date thinks you are.

This brings us to the question of which out of all the personal attributes (attractiveness, sincereity, intelligence, fun, ambition, and liking) is the most influential for the final decision? For this, we will run a linear regression model.

From the regression above, we see that being intelligent, sincere, or having similar interests slightly hurts your chances at getting a second date. This seems a little counterintuitive, but may have something to do with the 4 minute speed dating time limit. This might suggest that when it comes to first dates, to focus on being fun and likeable if the goal is to get a second date.

Let's run an OLS model with both respondents' ratings instead of only one side, this time with the dependent variable being match instead of decision.

From the coefficients above, it looks that what really matters is the decision of both participants in securing a second date, rather than what their ratings were of one another. This may seem a little trivial, but by construction it would stand to reason that the most important determinant in whether a pairing will match is whether or not they both select each other in the final decision, not necessarily how they rated everyone present at the speed dating experiment in absolute terms.

Given how much the respondent likes that the partner and what the respondent's decision is, we have an 82.5% accuracy in predicting a match on both training and validation sets using logistic regression. This makes sense given that we know only 26% of people were heartbroken. If you liked someone in this experiment, odds were that they liked you back.

Let's try more models to see if we can get a better match prediction.

Conclusion¶

This data exploration didn't really give us any better answers to the secrets of love, or at least mastering the first date. It's not shared interests or hobbies, it's not attractiveness or intelligence or other commonly thought to be important traits. It's just how much someone likes you, which we see reflected in the variables dec_o and dec.

To summarize, we learned:

  • Both genders represented in this study like dinner + a movie
  • Women are more selective
  • Both genders have skewed perceptions of what the opposite sex values
  • A match happens more often than unrequited love
  • Attractiveness does not factor into rejection
  • Your impression of yourself is not what other people think of you
  • There is no key secret to being likeable in any of the traits measured in this study
  • Being likeable is the most important component of securing a second date
